## Security
- Never introduce secrets, tokens, credentials, or sensitive identifiers.
- Never weaken authentication, authorization, or encryption.
- Treat all external input as untrusted.
- Never disable security checks unless explicitly instructed.
- Security requirements override existing project patterns when in conflict.

## Boundaries
- Do not modify .cursorignore unless explicitly instructed to do so for that purpose.
- Do not create, modify, or suggest Git commits unless explicitly requested.
- Do not add new dependencies unless explicitly requested or approved.
- Do not delete files unless explicitly asked.
- Do not refactor unrelated code.
- Do not perform refactors, cleanups, or optimizations unless required to achieve the stated goal.
- If it is unclear whether a change is required or allowed by these rules, ask for clarification before proceeding.

## Style & Changes
- Follow existing project patterns and conventions.
- Prefer explicit, readable code over clever or implicit behavior.
- Match existing formatting and idioms.
- Keep changes minimal, localized, and targeted to the stated goal.
- Avoid large or wide‑ranging diffs unless explicitly requested.
